Did you know that, in Old Russia, people steamed in an oven?

It seems to be an impossible question. After all, they cooked food in the oven and slept on its sleeping platforms, but they usually steamed in a bathhouse (‚Äòbanya‚Äô). That‚Äôs all true, but there is one nuance. If, for some reason, it was not possible to build a bathhouse, they really did steam in their ovens!

It was not for nothing that the Russian stove oven took up a significant part of the hut - it not only held pots of food, but also several adults could climb in at the same time. In addition, using it as a steam room helped save money: the oven was heated every day, there was no need to spend money on firewood for the bathhouse.

At the end of the day, when all the household chores were finished and the oven had cooled down a little, all the ashes were removed from there. Then they laid straw in the crucible or ‚Äògornylo‚Äô (that's what its interior was called) and put a cast-iron container with hot water. After that, all that was left was to climb inside and close the damper. Wet the broom thoroughly in hot water and sprinkle it around to create steam.

This method is also mentioned in the ‚ÄòLife of St. Irinarkhus‚Äô from the end of the 16th century: deacon Onuphrius of the Nikitsky Monastery suffered from fever and was so shivery that he climbed into his oven to warm up a little. So, the oven was not only a nurse, but also a kind of "hospital": sick people could be carried inside on planks. Even sick babies were placed in the oven to expel diseases. How can one not to remember ‚ÄòBaba Yaga‚Äô!
Steaming in the oven also had its own peculiarities. People usually climbed in with their feet inside. It was necessary to sit or lie in it very carefully, so as not to burn oneself on the walls. They did not use much water - they doused themselves in a trough standing near the stove oven. The men steamed first and then the women and children.
Surprisingly, people used to steam in ovens not only in ancient times, but even in the first half of the 20th century.

Credit: Public domain, Nikolay Anokhin (CC BY-SA 4.0), Ivan Gorokhov
